nd tenure as a set of twelve propositions. Inferences are derived from these propositions by a set of transfer formulas that govern the way in which static knowledge about land tenure can be applied to new disputes. After deriving this descriptive system by extensive observation of the Trobrianders' land courts and by interrogation of litigants, Hutchins provides a test of his grammar by showing how it can be used to simulate decisions in new cases. What is most interesting about these simulations, generally, is that they require all the same logical operations that arise from a careful analysis of Western thought. Looking closely at "primitive" inference in a natural situation, Hutchins finds that Trobriand reasoning is no more primitive than our own.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Nov 2021) 0aCognitie. 0aCognition and culture. 0aCultuur. 0aEthnological jurisprudence. 0aEthnologie juridique. 0aEthnologie. 0aEthnology. 0aGeschichte der übrigen Welt. 0aGeschichte der übrigen Welt. 0aLand tenure. 0aLandrechten. 4aCognition and culture -- Papua New Guinea -- Trobriand Islands. 4aCross-cultural comparison. 4aEthnological jurisprudence. 4aEthnology -- Papua New Guinea -- Trobriand Islands. 4aLand tenure (Primitive law) -- Papua New Guinea -- Trobriand Islands. 7aPSYCHOLOGY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Complete eBook Packagez9783110353488oZDB-23-HCO08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP e-dition: Science eBook Packagez9783110353549oZDB-23-HSP08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z97831104422120 cprintz978067441863940uhttps://doi.org/10.4159/harvard.978067441866040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674418660423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674418660/